{
  "text": "The way in which the modelers initially interact with the participants in the social setting can greatly influence the results in participatory modeling processes [CITATION_1] . Mehrotra and Grossman [CITATION_2] provide an example where trust earned from the frontline workers of the client organization was essential for successful communication and problem identification. Social phenomena which occur in groups also include the contagion of emotions. This phenomenon can naturally play a role when the people engaged in the modeling process meet and communicate with each other. Contagion of positive mood has been found to increase cooperation and decrease conflicts in group problem solving [CITATION_3] . Yet, contagion of positive mood does not necessarily improve the modeling process as elevated positivity can reduce critical thinking and cause groupthink [CITATION_4] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "15866896",
